In Java, **method overloading** allows a class to have **multiple methods with the same name** but **different parameter lists** (number, type, or order of parameters). This enables **compile-time polymorphism**, where the method that gets executed is determined by the compiler based on the method arguments.

**Syntax:**

```java
returnType methodName(paramType1 a) { ... }
returnType methodName(paramType1 a, paramType2 b) { ... }
```

---
**Example:**
```java
// Class with simple overloaded methods
class Greet {

    // Method with no parameters
    void sayHello() {
        System.out.println("Hello!");
    }

    // Overloaded method with one parameter
    void sayHello(String name) {
        System.out.println("Hello, " + name + "!");
    }
}

// Main class to run the program
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create an object of Greet
        Greet g = new Greet();

        // Call the no-argument method
        g.sayHello();             // Prints: Hello!

        // Call the overloaded method with a name
        g.sayHello("Amit");       // Prints: Hello, Amit!
    }
}
```

